  "output": "This is a pure Python codebase (async job-scraper + SQLite dedup store, no frontend) — so the \"React re-renders\" ask doesn't apply here; I've noted that below rather than fabricating findings. Here's what I found in the code that exists:\n\n## 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:55-74` (`Store.diff`)\n\nFor every job in the batch (potentially hundreds — Amazon/Microsoft/Google fetchers alone can each return 400+), it issues a separate `SELECT ... WHERE key = ?` round-trip:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    for job in jobs:\n        row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n        ...\n```\n\nThis is a classic N+1: N SQLite round-trips (each with query-planning overhead) instead of one. Fix — batch-load existing hashes into a dict first, then do the diff in memory:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    existing = {}\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 900):  # stay under SQLite's default 999-param limit\n        chunk = keys[i:i + 900]\n        qs = \",\".join(\"?\" * len(chunk))\n        for row in self.conn.execute(\n                f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({qs})\", chunk):\n            existing[row[\"key\"]] = row[\"content_hash\"]\n\n    new, changed, seen_only = [], [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        h = existing.get(job.key)\n        if h is None:\n            new.append(job)\n        elif h != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job)\n        else:\n            seen_only.append(job.key)\n\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n    cur.executemany(\"INSERT INTO jobs (...) VALUES (...)\", [{**j.to_row(), \"now\": now} for j in new])\n    cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET ... WHERE key=:key\", [{**j.to_row(), \"now\": now} for j in changed])\n    cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", [(now, k) for k in seen_only])\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nThis turns O(N) round-trips into O(N/900) selects + 3 batched `executemany` calls — the biggest win in the codebase given this runs every 12h per the scheduled job.\n\n## 2. Redundant computation — `filters.py:11-41` (regex recompiled per job)\n\n`match()` calls `_compile(include)` and `_compile(exclude)` **on every job**, recompiling the same keyword regexes from scratch each time:\n\n```python\ndef match(job: Job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...):\n    ...\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):  # recompiled every call\n```\n\nFor a filter list of ~10 keywords run over ~1,000 fetched jobs, that's ~10,000 unnecessary `re.compile` calls per run. Fix — compile once in `filter_jobs` and pass the compiled patterns down:\n\n```python\ndef match(job: Job, *, include: list[re.Pattern] | None = None,\n          exclude: list[re.Pattern] | None = None, ...) -> bool:\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    ...\n\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    cutoff = ...\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude, ...)]\n```\n\n## 3. Caching opportunity — `models.py:66-69` (`Job.content_hash`)\n\n`content_hash` is a plain `@property` doing a SHA-256 hash of concatenated fields, but it's computed twice per changed job in `store.py`: once in `diff()`'s comparison (`row[\"content_hash\"] != job.content_hash`) and again inside `_update()`'s `to_row()`. Hashing is cheap per-call, so this isn't hot today, but it's free to fix and matters once field lists grow:\n\n```python\n@dataclass(slots=True)\nclass Job:\n    ...\n    _content_hash: str | None = field(default=None, repr=False, compare=False)\n\n    @property\n    def content_hash(self) -> str:\n        if self._content_hash is None:\n            blob = \"|\".join((self.title, self.location, self.url, self.department))\n            self._content_hash = hashlib.sha256(blob.encode()).hexdigest()[:16]\n        return self._content_hash\n```\n(Needs an explicit slot since `slots=True` blocks `functools.cached_property`.) Low priority — only worth it if `to_row()` call sites multiply.\n\n## 4. Sequential HTTP pagination — `fetchers.py` (twosigma/optiver/google/microsoft/netflix/amazon)\n\nEach of these fetchers pages sequentially with `for page_n in range(max_pages): await _get_json(...)`, stopping when a page returns nothing new. This is inherent to \"unknown total pages, stop when empty\" logic, not a bug — but note it means wall-clock per source scales with page count × request latency, serialized. If any of these boards regularly return their full `max_pages` (e.g. Amazon/Microsoft capped at 40), that's 40 sequential round-trips for one company while `fetch_all`'s `Semaphore(concurrency)` lets *other companies* run in parallel. Not worth restructuring unless a specific source is measured as slow — flagging for awareness, not a fix.\n\n## 5. Memory leaks — none found\n\nNo unbounded caches, no unclosed resources: `httpx.AsyncClient` is closed in `fetch_all`'s `finally` block when it owns the client, `Store` is always used as a context manager (`with Store(...) as store`) and closes its `sqlite3.Connection`, and `notify_email`'s `smtplib.SMTP` is also a context manager. This is a short-lived CLI/cron script (not a long-running server), so there's no accumulation surface for the classic leak patterns to bite.\n\n## 6. React re-renders — N/A\n\nNo React/JS frontend exists in this repo (`modes/*.md` are prompt files for Claude, not application code). Nothing to analyze here.\n\n---\n\n**Priority**: fix #1 (N+1 in `Store.diff`) first — it's the one with real, measurable impact given this runs on a schedule against a growing `jobs.db`. #2 is a quick, safe win. #3 is optional polish.\n",
